    The process of creating racial categories in the first place is known as racial formation, defined as ```the sociohistorical process by which racial categories are created, inhabited, transformed, and destroyed''' \parencite[Omi \& Winant, 1986, as cited in][p.~466]{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997}.
    European colonialism is commonly cited as the exact colonial period through which this sociohistorical process played out (\citeauthor[Boggs, 1970; Cox, 1948; Furnivall, 1948; Bagubane, 1990; E. Williams, 1944/1961; R. Williams, 1990, as cited in][]{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997}, \citeyear[p.~473]{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997}; \citeauthor[Stoler, 1995, as cited in][]{rosa_unsettling_2017}, \citeyear[p.~623]{rosa_unsettling_2017}) and sometimes specifically colonialism in the Americas \parencite[Quijano, 1993, as cited in][p.~326]{grosfoguel_race_2004}.
    However, the racialization of people is a possible result of any colonial enterprise.
    Indeed, as \textcite{casanova_internal_1965} argued before the racial formation perspective was developed, ``Racism and racial discrimination are the historical legacy of the conquest of some peoples by others, from antiquity to the expansion of the great empires and colonial systems of the modern era'' (p.~31).
    Even earlier, Lenin (1916) described Rome as partaking in colonialism, furthermore stating that it was built on slavery \parencite[as cited in][p.~113]{wolpe_theory_1975}, which suggests the same circumstances that propelled racial formation during European colonialism.
    Colonialism or colonial-like activities are that which is important in analyzing the arrival of racialized categories.

    The reason colonialism is so important in the process of racial formation is that it allows for such an extreme form of othering of groups of people that they are conceptualized in society as human but less human than the colonizers, hence a separate race.
    Race becomes something that is inherent to Others and defines essential characteristics about them.
    Once the racial formation process has played out, it becomes self-perpetuating, meaning it will continue even in the absence of an official colonial administration.
    In fact, once created, racial categories become available for self-identification just as any other social category is despite also being imposed by from the outside \parencite[pp.~471-472]{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997}, hence African-Americans' attempts at co-opting labels that have been attached to them such as through the Black pride movement \parencite{smith_changing_1992}.
    It is not surprising, then, that essentialist beliefs about race have persisted up to the present time in former European colonies despite the end of direct colonialism (\foreign{e.g.}, \citeauthor{hoffman_racial_2016}, \citeyear[p.~4297]{hoffman_racial_2016}; \citeauthor[Roth et al., 2019, as cited in][]{roth_conceptualizations_2023}, \citeyear[p.~45]{roth_conceptualizations_2023}).
    Essentialist views have even been found to persist among researchers in genetics, biology, and anthropology \parencite{roth_conceptualizations_2023}.
    Ideological racism is not necessarily entailed by essentialist views despite the two being associated \parencite[p.~45]{roth_conceptualizations_2023}, but essentialist beliefs are harmful even in the absence of ideological racism.
