    The definition of racism itself has also changed.
    Up through the 1990s, R. Benedict's (1945) definition of racism as ``the dogma that one ethnic group is condemned by nature to congenital inferiority and another group is destined to congenital superiority'' had been the norm that was used in research \parencite[as cited in][p.~465]{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997}, though today this would be specifically called ideological racism.
    Importantly, when treating racism as exclusively this sort of irrational ideology, it leaves education as the only solution to alleviated racism, ignoring any rational aspects of the social system that engender this ideology in the first place \parencite[p.~468]{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997}.
    The racialized social systems framework thus shifts racism from an irrational personal ideology to a rational structure that creates lower life chances for those placed into a subordinate racialized category \parencite[p.~470]{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997}.
    For instance, undocumented Latinx workers in the US generally benefit the economy as a whole \parencite{becerra_fear_2012, edwards_economic_2017}.
    Those who worry about the human rights violations that may occur if mass deportation were carried out have used this benefit as an argument against mass deportation \parencite{shanker_trumps_2024}.
    Likewise, the cost of carrying out mass deportation has been used as an argument in favor of keeping undocumented workers in the US \parencite{american_immigration_council_mass_2024}.
    However, lost in this discussion is that the position of these workers leads to their exploitation where they receive low wages for dangerous work and have little access to healthcare and welfare services \parencite{salinas_systemic_2022}.
    In effect, both those who are against allowing undocumented workers to stay in the US and those who are for keeping them in the country perpetuate a racialized social system that provides these workers with unequal life chances.
