    \subsection{Colonialism}
      \label{sec:colonialism}
      Colonialism or colonial-like systems are the hallmark of race and, as such, represent that which most distinguishes race from ethnicity.
      To understand if a social category is a racialized category, it is thus important to have an understanding of what colonialism looks like.
      A colony itself has been defined as ``a territory occupied by emigrants from a `mother' country'' who exercise dominance ``over indigenous populations'' in ``economic, ... military, political, and spiritual'' terms \parencite[pp.~28-30]{casanova_internal_1965}.
      These colonized territories are forcibly placed under the management of a dominant society that either transforms or destroys the local culture and racializes the colonized to justify treating them as a subordinate class \parencite[Blauner, 1972, as cited in][p.~246]{pinderhughes_toward_2011}.
      Colonized people are then kept at subsistence levels of living and used as cheap or free labor for a single economic resource without any meaningful ownership of said resource.
      These limitations help ensure a dependence on the colonizers.
      When those who have been colonized challenge this dependency, violence may be used to maintain control \parencite[pp.~30-31]{casanova_internal_1965}, again justified under the belief that the colonized people are a lesser form of human.

      The idea that some version of this traditional, direct, explicit colonialism continues beyond the abolishment of the colonial administration has been present for some time in the US even if not always referred to as internal colonialism.
      Du Bois (1944/1985) argued that such universal traits of colonized and semi-colonized people included facing physical and/or psychological violence, economic exploitation, poverty, lawlessness, crime, illiteracy, disaster, disease, starvation, death, disenfranchisement, and denial of cultural equality \parencite[as cited in][p.~87]{rabaka_web_2007}.
      The lot of African-Americans has therefore been compared to that of colonized people \parencite[Cruse, 1962, as cited in][p.~239]{pinderhughes_toward_2011}.
      The idea was also embraced by the Black Power movement in the late 1960s \parencite[p.~240]{pinderhughes_toward_2011}.
      In terms of activism, colonialism functions both as a comprehensible analogy for expressing the difficulties that a group faces and as a way to develop solidarity with colonized and formerly colonized people in other parts of the world.
      % R. Allen (1969) incorporated social class within the colonized group (as cited in Pinderhughes 2011:249)

      Sociologists have been explicitly developing the concept of internal colonialism since the 1960s.
      It was initially defined as the domination and exploitation of one class of natives by another class of natives in a society after that society had experienced domination and exploitation at the hands of foreigners \parencite[p.~27]{casanova_internal_1965}.
      This dominated class of natives has been conceived of as a nation within a nation \parencite[p.~237]{pinderhughes_toward_2011}, which calls for the careful delineation of said nation when carrying out analyses.
      \textcite{pinderhughes_toward_2011} thus suggested that internally colonized nations be geographically defined (pp.~236/251), raising the possibility of there being many internally colonized nations.

      A more difficult dilemma is deciding whether an internal colony must be related to a former official colony.
      Early formulations held that an internal colony did indeed need to be a former official colony.
      \textcite{casanova_internal_1965}, for instance, stated that internal colonialism involves ``an encounter between two races, cultures, or civilizations, whose genesis and evolution occurred without any mutual contact up to one specific moment,'' which sets it apart from similar situations such as class conflicts or rural-urban conflicts, which may involve groups whose evolution has occurred with consistent contact between them, and is also what ``makes possible intensive racial and cultural discriminations'' (p.~33).
      However, this requirement of separate geneses could hold just as well in any immigration scenario, which is perhaps why a modified form of the original concept has been used by researchers who focus more on immigration, such as \textcite{grosfoguel_race_2004} who proposed the idea of ``colonial immigrant'' groups who find themselves lumped in with existing ``colonial/racial subjects'' by host societies, all of whom are then racialized (p.~323).
      Abandoning the criteria of being a former official colony, though, leaves one in a more precarious position when distinguishing the sort of conflicts that are born out of internal colonialism from any other sort of conflicts.

      Conflict is not solely the purview of race.
      Indeed, \textcite{eriksen_ethnicity_2010} argued that ethnicity had been growing in importance by the 21st century in social and political landscapes in part because of state-internal ethnic conflicts and ethnic migrations leading to conflicts (pp.~2-3).
      Similarly, \textcite{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997} acknowledged that racial, ethnic, and class conflicts all exist as their own types of conflict (pp.~469/471).
      He provided conflicts in Rwanda and the Balkans as examples of ethnic conflicts, though he did not attempt to formulate a diagnostic for identifying these conflicts as ethnic rather than anything else.
      For class conflicts, \textcite{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997} did offer more as he argued that class conflicts take precedence over racial conflicts only when ``economic, political, and social distance between races decreases substantially'' (p.~471).
      This argument, while it could also be used for analyzing class versus ethnic conflicts, is only applicable to societies in which racial conflict is already presumed to exist.
      In other words, this approach would not help to identify a conflict as a class conflict in and of itself much less help to distinguish between racial and ethnic conflict.

      The nature of what makes a conflict ethnic has received some attention in sociology, as well.
      \textcite{banton_ethnic_2000} in particular has discussed the difficulties in identifying ethnic conflicts as ethnic.
      He argued that describing a conflict as such implies that the conflict is best understood as being powered by ethnicity over anything else \parencite[p.~483]{banton_ethnic_2000}.
      For instance, the Troubles in Ireland may have appeared to be an ethnic conflict as one involved group was predominantly Catholic and the other predominantly Protestant, but this cannot be classified as an ethnic conflict in Banton's view because it was not that religious difference that caused the conflict in the first place but rather a history of disagreements over the sort of relationship that Ireland should have with England \parencite[p.~485]{banton_ethnic_2000}.
      Indeed, two groups in conflict, even if ethnically distinct, often have relationships along various other dimensions that could have more explanatory power.
      Banton's insistence on ethnicity being the driving force of the conflict before classifying it as ethnic conflict stands in stark contrast to scenarios where people have been racialized.
      Racializing people is seen a justification for colonial activities in modern racial theory and so would never function as the impetus behind a conflict.
      Indeed, even in the case of ethnic conflict, it is difficult to imagine ethnic identity itself as a motivating factor rather than more general intergroup disagreements.
      For instance, in the case of the Rwandan Tutsi genocide that \textcite{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997} identified as an ethnic conflict, the Tutsi were not killed simply because they were Tutsi but because there longstanding conflicts over access to resources in the country \parencite{magnarella_background_2005}.
      While Banton's approach to identifying conflicts as ethnic rather than non-ethnic would in fact function well as a diagnostic, its theoretical foundations are questionable.
      % When mobilisation efforts aim to reduce these dimensions to ethnicity only, that is one indication that a conflict is ethnic in nature \parencite{banton_ethnic_2000}, though not a sufficient condition in and of itself as that which is used to mobilise a group to action is not necessarily the same as that which motivates the mobilisers.

      Examining the desired outcomes of a conflict could also provide an indication of whether it is ethnic in that a conflict over control of a state cannot be ethnic as this is the feature along which ethnic groups and nations are distinguished.
      A nation is politically oriented \parencite[pp.~6-7]{anderson_imagined_2006}.
      It ``holds that political boundaries should be coterminous with cultural boundaries'' (Gellner, 1983), whereas a nation and an ethnic group are otherwise the same, both delineating groups according to shared culture \parencite[p.~10]{eriksen_ethnicity_2010}.
      This does not exclude ethnic conflicts from having political ends, but those political ends must not be taking over the state.
      Likewise, the sort of conflict inherent to internal colonialism (\foreign{i.e.}, racial conflict) is not restricted from having political components but must also not be specifically about overthrowing a state to install a new racio-state, so to speak.

      While ethnic conflicts have by some been identified by eliminating other motives behind a conflict, racial/colonial conflicts have been theorized more in terms of what they include.
      Racial/colonial conflicts, whether internal or traditional, involve exploitation and domination, making it especially important to establish how these conflicts differ from class conflicts \parencite[p.~108]{wolpe_theory_1975}.
      Indeed, at least in Marxist formulations, class is central to definitions of exploitation.
      Bettelheim (1972), for instance, defined exploitation as the expropriation of the surplus labor of one social class by another social class \parencite[as cited in][p.~110]{wolpe_theory_1975}.
      \textcite{wolpe_theory_1975}, unfortunately, did not offer much in terms of criteria for colonial exploitation specifically, although he did suggest plunder, the exchange of non-equivalents, and price formation practices as possible means of exploitation in colonialism (p.~112).

      The above does not offer much in the way of distinct criteria for distinguishing between class, ethnic, and racial/colonial conflicts, but some provisional conclusions can be operationalized for the purposes of the present study.
      Class conflicts and traditional colonial conflicts are easily distinguished in that, while both involve exploitation, the former is exploitation between social classes and the latter between independent nations, states, or nation-states.
      Internal colonial conflicts, on the other hand, look very much like class conflicts in that both involve expliotation of one group by another within a single society.
      Social class is also likely to be highly correlated with race in the case of internal colonial conflicts as an exploited racialized people will naturally become stuck in a lower social class.
      If internal colonialism is taken to only exist where groups had been involved in traditional colonialism, these similarities can be disentangled easily.
      If not -- if colonial immigrants are to be considered -- the inability of escaping the impact of the conflict for those whose social class is not that which places them in an exploitable position would indicate that the conflict does not have class as a basis.

      Ethnic conflicts, as conceptualized by sociologists such as Banton, are theoretically tenuous.
      The implication is that an ethnic conflict must necessarily be based on cultural ideology and nothing else.
      This, however, leaves unanswered the question of where such an ideology comes from in the first place, which was the theoretical problem that led to the reconceptualization of race and racism.
      The example of Rwanda as an ethnic conflict also resembles a racial/colonial conflict in that it centered on unequal access to resources and thus exploitation and domination.
      Indeed, while this is frequently presented as an ethnic conflict, \textcite{magnarella_background_2005} noted that the Hutu characterized the ``Tutsi as foreign exploiters, belonging to another race'' (p.~821), which would make this more of a racial/colonial conflict than an ethnic conflict.
      Abandoning the idea of ethnic conflict altogether is perhaps the best operationalization as this leaves racial/colonial conflict as any conflict that is based on exploitation and domination, justified by othering of some group of people for whom that othering is inescapable even if the exploitation has been escaped.

    \subsection{Race in the United States}
      \label{sec:united_states}
      While the specific social milieu that will be analyzed here is situated in mostly rural South Louisiana, it would be difficult to interpret the local categories Creole and Cajun without considering their place in the broader racial context of the country as a whole.
      Despite this area being historically considered isolated from the United States, the undoing of that isolation over time has in fact been a factor in not only the decline of F\&C in the state but also the reinterpretation of Creole and Cajun identities, as will be discussed in sections \ref{sec:creole_history} and \ref{sec:cajun_history}.
      For the present section, the discussion will roughly follow Marable's (2002) outlining of the four ``racial domains'' through which African-Americans have passed: slavery, Jim Crow, colonial ghettos, and finally neo-colonial ghettos \parencite[as cited in][]{pinderhughes_toward_2011}.
      This is not say that African-Americans are the only racialized people in the US but they hold a prominent position both in public discourse on race as well as in studies of racialization and so their plight over time is useful for contextualizing how race functions in the US.

      The European colonial enterprise in the Americas began with the exploitation of Others.
      This culminated most prominently with the enslavement of Africans who were then imported into the colonies to perform labor for Europeans colonists.
      The racialization of Africans undoubtedly came about to justify this gross human rights abuse.
      In total, it has been estimated that 9,778,500 enslaved people were imported into the Americas between 1450 and 1867, although it has also been estimated that those exported from Africa between 1450 and 1900 number 11,698,000 \parencite[p.~477]{lovejoy_volume_1982}.
      This implies that upwards of 1,919,500 live were lost just in the process of moving people.
      For the British colonies, these people ended making up a larger proportion of the southern population (39.8\%) than the middle (7.0\%) or the northern (3.1\%) \parencite[Franklin \& Moss, 1988, as cited in][p.~320]{rickford_prior_1997}.
      The territory of modern-day Louisiana, of course was not part of the British colonies but rather New France until the Louisiana Purchase of 1803.
      Between 1763 and 1800 Lower Louisiana was consistently divided almost evenly between free people and enslaved people \parencite[p.~279]{hall_africans_1992}.
      This is to say that the colonies in the Americas were ripe for the racialization not only of indigenous people but also of enslaved people.

      After the abolition of slavery, by which time Louisiana was well established as a US state, the Reconstruction era gave rise debates over how to integrate formerly enslaved people into society.
      One such debate was between W.E.B. Du Bois and Booker T. Washington, the former arguing for full inclusion into society and the latter for education to prepare for menial work \parencite[Morris, 2015, as cited in][p.~39]{ray_theory_2019}.
      Most Blacks in the US were not able to move up the social ladder towards full inclusion into society at that time by design, hence it has been argued that there were three social classes related to race: working-class Blacks, a small Black bourgeoisie, and Whites \parencite[R. Allen, 1969, as cited in][p.~249]{pinderhughes_toward_2011}.
      The Black bourgeoisie faced pressure from Whites to keep those in the lower social class under control, which helped them keep their own standing while still ensuring the racial hierarchy.
      This is perhaps a common feature in racialized social systems as a similar middle status group with a similar role, referred to as Morenos or Pardos, also developed in Brazil \parencite[Wade, 1997, as cited in][p.~901]{bonilla-silva_essential_1999} as well as in South Africa, referred to as Coloureds there \parencite[G. Lewis, 1987, as cited in][pp.~338-339]{root_beyond_1992}.
      Creoles in the Americas in general have also been described in similar terms \parencite[pp.~59-60]{anderson_imagined_2006}.
      A theme of oppression is that it often becomes entrenched in a way where it appears to be diminishing but is simply changing in appearance.

      A particularly vivid example of this change of appearance is the Jim Crow era in the US, which presented indications of improvement that either did not last, were not truly significant, or were simply new chains in disguise.
      For instance, the Communist Party USA was calling for the ``self-determination of the Negro nation'' as early as the 1920s, focusing on the Black Belt of the south no less, but had all but withdrawn such support by the time McCarthyism had entered full swing \parencite[p.~242]{pinderhughes_toward_2011}.
      Black banks were also established by the 1920s, but at their peak in 1926, they held only 0.2\% of the total US assets \parencite[Baradaran, 2017, as cited in][p.~38]{ray_theory_2019}, a meager amount which may be related to events such as the Tulsa Race Massacre of 1921 that led to the destruction of somewhere between \$32,000,000 and \$48,000,000 in property held by Blacks \parencite[p.~1]{albright_after_2021}.
      Historically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCUs) also started during Jim Crow, but were stunted due to southern legislators having the power to appoint board members, which meant supporters of Jim Crow were placed in these seats \parencite[Williamson, 2004, as cited in][p.~39]{ray_theory_2019}.
      Even the official end of Jim Crow with the passage of the Civil Rights Act in 1964 has been described as the end of the colonial administration in the US but not the end of the colonial situation \parencite[pp.~325-326]{grosfoguel_race_2004}.
      With that act, the racialized social system of the US changed its appearance once more while continuing to create unequal life chances for racialized groups up to the present despite increasing diversity and a reduction in overt acts of intolerance.

      Census records for the United States suggest that diversity has increased, shifting from 1 in 8 people being non-White to 1 in 4.
      When including Latinxs, the ratio becomes 1 in 3 \parencite[pp.~25-26]{fischer_century_2006}.
      This pattern holds through the 2020s with the difference that non-Whites increased to 42\% of the population when including Latinxs.
      Latinxs have indeed become the largest non-White group at 19.5\% of the population, followed by Blacks at 13.7\% \parencite{noauthor_us_2020}.
      At level of the neighborhood, census records suggested that the proportion of White-dominated neighborhoods in the country decreased from 66.0\% to 42.5\% between 1990 and 2010, which may be driven by immigrants mostly settling in highly populous metropolitan areas \parencite[pp.~175-176]{wright_patterns_2014}.
      All of these increases in diversity have also been apparent to White Americans.
      Already by 2000, ``roughly half'' of White Americans thought they were part of a minority group \parencite[Alba et al., 2005, as cited in][p.~437]{smith_social_2014}.
      This increased diversity coupled with Whites' belief that they represent a minority group may have led to a backlash against efforts to solve systemic inequalities.
      As \textcite{omi_racial_1997} observed among White college students in the late 1990s, in apparent resentment, they questioned their own racial identities in response to seeing programs and initiatives in place meant to help non-White groups (p.~20).
      % Ethnic and racial diversity, measured with Shannon entropy using census records, has increased between 1990 and 2010 (0.4576 > 0.6015) (Wright et al. 2014:175)
      % Growth in the Latinx population in 2011 was driven more by births than by immigration (Pew Hispanic Center 2011, as cited in Wright et al. 2014:181)

      Though in general the US has has experienced improved relations in terms of outwardly expressed tolerance of racial minorities between the 1970s and the 2010s \parencite[Bobo et al., 2012; Firebaugh \& Davis, 1988, as cited in][p.~437]{smith_social_2014}, there are still signs of persistent systemic problems.
      Racial income inequality had been decreasing earlier in the 20th century but stalled by 2000 \parencite[Leicht, 2008, as cited in][p.~436]{smith_social_2014}.
      As an example of what this looks like at the local level, \textcite{van_hofwegen_coming_2010} reported that 71\% of African-American youths lived below the poverty line during the years 1990 to 2006 in their longitudinal study in Chapel Hill, North Carolina (p.~431).
      These systemic issues become readily apparent in cases where both Blacks and Whites should face similar hurdles to good life outcomes but do not.
      In New York City, for example, it was found that Blacks with criminal records had more difficulty obtaining employment than Whites who also had criminal records \parencite[Pager, 2007; Pager et al., 2009, as cited in][p.~41]{ray_theory_2019}.
      Pronouncements of racist ideology may not be prevalent in the US anymore, but this has not led to the deracialization of the social system.
      % Increased tolerance has also dovetailed into exploitation for profit through phenomena such as linguistic minstrelsy \parencite{bucholtz_performing_2011, eberhardt_first_2015}.
      % These continued issues tend to focus on African-Americans for obvious reasons: the history of slavery in the US and its reverberations are going to be felt most clearly by the group whose ancestors were the primary group that was enslaved.
      % As will be seen in Section \ref{sec:race_sociolinguistics}, race and ethnicity in sociolinguistics has also been mostly centered on African-Americans when studies are based in the US.
      % White teenagers in general perform AAL \parencite[C. Cutler 2002, as cited in][]{cutler_hip-hop_2007}

      Racist ideologies, in fact, do not need to be pronounced in a society where Whiteness is treated as unmarked as in the US.
      \citeauthor{omi_racial_1997}'s (\citeyear{omi_racial_1997}) observation of White college students indeed exemplifies that Whites in the US have been in a position to not have to concern themselves with their own racial identity.
      Likewise, Statistical Policy Directive 15 in the US, which sets standards for federal racial and ethnic data, linked Blacks to racial groups in Africa whereas no such reference was made linking Whites to European groups nor any other groups \parencite[p.~11]{omi_racial_1997}, implying that once Whiteness is achieved, a group's ancestry no longer matters.
      It is perhaps for this reason that \textcite{waters_ethnic_1990} reported that her White participants saw their ethnicities as ``flexible and symbolic and voluntary'' whereas that was not the case for non-Whites (p.~156).
      This unmarked character of Whiteness also carries over into organizations such as evangelicals (Bracey, 2016) and the National Rifle Association (Zakrison et al., 2017) \parencite[as cited in][p.~46]{ray_theory_2019}.
      In this situation, the markedness applied to non-Whites is itself enough to establish legitimacy for the racist idea that being White is what one should strive for.
      % The Census Bureau concluded that 40% of Hispanics in the US answered incorrectly for their race and ethnicity in 1980 and 1990 because they didn't choose both an ethnicity and a race (Omi 1997:14)

      In sum, the racialization of the United States began before the country was even founded.
      Indigenous and enslaved people were exploited from the moment Europeans landed in the Americas, and that exploitation was justified by racializing them as lesser than (White) Europeans.
      While there have been both changes in laws (\foreign{e.g.}, the abolition of slavery, the undoing of Jim Crow laws) and in the acceptabillity of expressing explicitly racist ideology in public, significant systemic problems have persisted that still result in unequal life outcomes for racialized groups.
      Whiteness remains a privileged status in the US against which other racial identities are measured.

      % In section \ref{sec:race_ethnicity}, it was stated that the assumed definition for race in this study strongly implicates phenotypes, and while I do not wish to immediately backtrack from that definition, it must be acknowledged that racial labeling in the United States is not always so focused on appearance.
      % For example, it has been pointed out that lighter skinned Black people exist who are still considered Black on account of factors such as ancestry and culture \parencite[p.~1]{susberry_racial_2004}.
      % Indeed, bi- and multi-racial individuals may not fit physical prototypical molds for the neat, discrete racial categories into which they are sometimes placed as a result of their racially diverse backgrounds.
      % Americans may not be consciously considering culture when asked racially to categorize individuals, but perhaps this consideration will become more conscious as the US becomes more and more diverse.

    \subsection{Race in sociolinguistics}
      \label{sec:race_sociolinguistics}
      Race has been analyzed in sociolinguistics and language variation studies as far back as the foundational works in the field.
      \textcite{labov_social_2006} considered Italians, Jewish people \parencite{labov_social_2006, labov_contraction_1969, labov_sociolinguistic_1972}, and African-Americans in New York City while \textcite{wolfram_sociolinguistic_1969} looked at African-Americans in Detroit, for instance.
      The field progressed in its treatment of race in much the same way as the field in general did, from the macrosociological level to the ethnographic and local level to social meaning-oriented work \parencite{eckert_three_2012}, but race in language has had its own indiosyncracies in how it has been approached over time.
      Importantly, only more recently have sociological frameworks such as racial formation \parencite{omi_racial_2015} and racialized social systems \parencite{bonilla-silva_rethinking_1997} found their way into sociolinguistics, most notably with the raciolinguistics proposal that aimed to reformulate approaches to racialized language \parencite{rosa_unsettling_2017}.

      Much of the research that came out of the first wave of sociolinguistics was aimed at showing that the languages used by racialized groups were indeed logical and rule-bound.
      This does not mean that they did not touch on connections to social issues, but social issues were not yet the focus of this work.
      For instance, \textcite{labov_social_2006} analyzed Italians, Jewish people, and African-Americans in New York City and found that they all had their own vowel usage patterns in English.
      Notably, for some of the ongoing vowel changes in New York City, African-American usage ``follow[ed] an entirely different pattern'' \parencite[p.~247]{labov_social_2006}, which could most likely be interpreted as an expression of the segregation between Black and White Americans.
      Although this was not a point Labov seemed to be attempting to make, it was nonetheless an important social finding present in that early work.
      It is also notable that race and ethnicity were treated as synonyms during the first wave of sociolinguistics.
      Indeed, \textcite{labov_social_2006} said of the groups mentioned above that they constituted ``the three \emph{ethnic groups} large enough to be studied in the sample'' [italics mine] (p.~180), though one could argue that all three were racialized at one time or another in the US \parencite{roediger_working_2018}.

      While first wave studies of language variation went a long way towards reducing the stigma attached to minority varieties, some of the framing was still problematic.
      One of those framings was the regular use of the qualifier \lexi{non-standard} for varieties spoken mostly by minority groups \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][p.~715]{labov_contraction_1969}, but perhaps the most significant framing issue was the idea that African-American Language (AAL) was a single monolithic variety, which may have simply been the good intention of wanting to demonstrate the logical structure of AAL being taken too far.
      Fieldwork on AAL from locations as varied as Philadelphia, Chicago, Detroit, Cleveland, and Los Angeles were all described as essentially the same language variety with only a few minor variations \parencite[p.~715]{labov_contraction_1969}.
      Even by the 1990s, well into the second wave of sociolinguistics, African-American speech was still being described, for example, as ``the uniform grammar used by African Americans who have minimal contact with other dialects typically in contexts where only speakers of that vernacular are present'' \parencite[Labov, 1998, as cited in][p.~165]{benor_ethnolinguistic_2010} or as a continuum, called African-American English in this case, ranging from essentially the privileged varieties in American English to African-American Vernacular English \parencite[Rickford, 1999, as cited in][p.~165]{benor_ethnolinguistic_2010}.
      Such aggregating of the speech of disparate groups of people risked being a source of erasure not only of distinct ways of speaking but of the distinct identities that are attached to those ways of speaking.

      The second wave of sociolinguistics was said to have begun with \textcite{milroy_language_1987} \parencite[p.~91]{eckert_three_2012}.
      The attention that AAL received during the first wave diminished during this time, and what work was being done in that area involved more fine-grained analyses.
      For example, \textcite{rickford_addressee-_1994} examined constraints on style shifting relative to the race of an African-American woman's interlocutors.
      In zooming in to more local contexts, more local social categories also became the focus.
      In one case tangentially related to the current study, the verbal morphology of ``Cajun Vernacular English'' was analyzed not only on its own but in relation to White southern varities as well as AAL, suggesting a complex relationship between Cajuns and these other groups.
      However, while local categories such as Cajun were being considered, they were not receiving the sort of close critical treatment that they merited.
      Cajun identity itself was thus not defined at all in \textcite{dubois_verbal_2003} but instead implied to simply be the identity of Whites in South Louisiana.

      The usefulness of social categories such as ethnicity was examined during the second wave, as well.
      \textcite{horvath_delimiting_1987}, although not working on language in the US, explicitly discussed the utility of ethnicity as a social variable.
      They argued that ethnicity is not well defined because it might have varying degrees of influence depending on which immigration generation one is in as well as between those in the same immigration generation but from different communities \parencite[p.~183]{horvath_delimiting_1987}.
      In the latter point, they were avoiding the trappings that earlier researchers fell into when establishing AAL as a monolith.
      They were also making immigration the central factor in ethnic group formation, similar to what \textcite{labov_social_2006} had implicitly done by singling out Italians in New York City.
      This aligned with the emphasis that A. D. Smith (1986) was placing on immigration for the formation of ethnic identities at that time \parencite[as cited in][p.~903]{bonilla-silva_essential_1999}.
      Indeed, both \textcite{weber_economy_1978} and \textcite{eriksen_ethnicity_2010}, discussed in Section \ref{sec:race_ethnicity}, also highlighted contact as a necessary condition for ethnic identities to form, as does the concept of enregisterment from the third wave of sociolinguistics for named language varieties \parencite{agha_social_2003, johnstone_mobility_2006}.
      The point being that, by the end of the second wave, researchers had begun to be more cognizant of the need to reconsider how social variables are used and understood, and that included ethnicity even if race was not being prominently addressed.
      % By the end of the second wave, Rickford in particular was trying to encourage socioliguists to use their positions and knowledge (that they've by and large gained via the good will of minority groups) to give back to minority communities (e.g., Rickford 1997 "Unequal")

      The third wave of sociolinguistics turned the focus of research towards social meaning and local categories even more so, making it perhaps not surprising that race has been examined more carefully during this phase.
      This includes attempts to correct early framings of AAL that treated it as a monolith.
      Indeed, the data needed to conclude that AAL is not a monolith had been present and available for some time already but was not interpreted as suggesting that there was variation between groups of AAL speakers.
      As \textcite{jones_toward_2015} pointed out, for example, \textcite{labov_language_1972} found non-rhoticity among some speakers in New York City but \textcite{riney_linguistic_1990} found full rhoticity Waterloo, Iowa (p.~404).
      Likewise, \textcite{rickford_addressee-_1994} reported that Foxy Brown, an individual African-American woman from the California Bay Area, exceeded the cumulative total use of invariant habitual \lexi{be} by all of the speakers analyzed in New York City \parencite{labov_study_1968}, Detroit \parencite{wolfram_sociolinguistic_1969}, and Brazos Valley, Texas \parencite{bailey_decreolization_1987} (p.~254), although no acknowledgement was made that this may be an indication of these simply being different varieties of AAL.
      By the 2010s, in contrast, findings on AAL were being argued as suggesting that there is regional variation despite the existence of ``supra-regional'' features that are shared in all regions that are not part of European American speech \parencite[p.~232]{wolfram_american_2016}, and work had begun on mapping out these regional variations \parencite{jones_toward_2015}.

      More relevant to the current study is that third wave studies have still rarely dealt with racialization but rather used race and ethnicity as synonyms.
      For instance, \citeauthor{wolfram_american_2016}'s (\citeyear{wolfram_american_2016}) review started out by stating, ``African American English (AAE) is the paradigmatic case of ethnicity-based language diversity'' (p.~217), although African-Americans themselves had been at the center of sociological work on racialization since \textcite{omi_racial_2015}.
      Likewise, \textcite{becker_linguistic_2014} framed her study of AAL as a study of an ethnolect rather than a raciolect or racialized variety in stating, ``African American English (AAE) is the quintessential ethnolect in North American sociolinguistics'' (p.~44).
      This framing pattern can be seen widely in sociolinguistic literature.
      \textcite{reyes_appropriation_2005} mostly discussed both Asian and African American identities as racial while also occasionally framing these as part of ethnic studies, and \textcite{rahman_middle-class_2008} explicitly equated race and ethnicity while framing African-American identity as an ethnic identity.
      In the case of \textcite{wolfram_american_2016}, statements such as ``contact between whites and blacks over the generations may have resulted in speakers of both ethnicities picking up features of one another'' (p.~225) make it clear that they were treating race and ethnicity as one and the same.
      This approach, where race and ethnicity are synonyms, and relatedly Black and African-American are often synonyms, makes it all but impossible to analyze the racialization of certain peoples as well as the racialization of their ways of speaking.
      % Save for few exceptions, such as \textcite{bucholtz_white_2010} who argued that ``race is ideologically grounded ... in biological differences'' and ethnicity in ``cultural differences'' (pp.~5-6), the distinction between race and ethnicity is little mentioned in sociolinguistics, which is relevant to this study in that it aims to fill that gap by offering a more intersectional analysis of these two social categories.
      % At times in Mendoza (2008), ethnicity appears as basically a synonym for race or national heritage
        % Speaking of a discussion with a participant, Mendoza-Denton (2008) explains "that she does not think of herself as ethnically or racially white" (124)
        % Explaining a participant who said that the parents of Norteñxs "are, one American, and one Mexican, much of the time," Mendoza-Denton (2008) says that Norteñxs are understood "as being ethnically mixed" (123)

      \citeauthor{wolfram_american_2016}'s (\citeyear{wolfram_american_2016}) statement also raises the question of crossing racial and ethnic boundaries, which has also been a focal point for third wave sociolinguistics that is relevant to behavior that will be seen among participants of the current study.
      This phenomenon had more or less been coined near the end of the second wave of sociolinguistics as \lexi{crossing}, a general term that refers to when a speaker switches to any language code that is not considered to belong to them regardless of what class of people own said language code, so to speak \parencite{rampton_crossing:_1995}.
      However, crossing refers to a sort of momentary code-switching rather than one's primary language being that which does not typically align with their social identity, both of which have been dealt with in the literature, often, though not always, in terms of the use of AAL.

      Given the glottonym African-American Language, the presumed owning group for this variety is African-Americans, though as C. Cutler (2002) put it, White people ``can and do pass for native speakers of AAE'' \parencite[as cited in][p.~529]{cutler_hip-hop_2007}.
      How such boundary crossing is characterized can depend on the direction in which it is occurring.
      It has been argued that in studies of African-Americans using linguistic features that index White identities, researchers conceptualize this as assimilation, but in studies of White people using African-American features \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][]{bucholtz_you_1999}, researchers conceptualize this as indexing African-American qualities that these speakers admire \parencite[p.~27]{eckert_where_2008}.
      Such framing helps to reify the position of Whites at the top of the racial hierarchy.
      As \textcite{bucholtz_white_2010} poignantly -- and perhaps ironically -- stated in her analysis of White youths constructing their identities through the use of AAL features, ``The hegemony of whiteness is typically exerted not by calling attention to white racial dominance but instead by treating whiteness as unremarkable -- even unnoticeable'' (p.~15).

      Not all boundary crossing studies have looked at White people using AAL features nor even implicated AAL at all.
      In Philadelphia, Asian American youths were seen using AAL features to varying degrees to thread the delicate needle of finding their place in the racial system of the United States \parencite{reyes_appropriation_2005}.
      In the South Carolina Sea Island, a pair of speakers, one White and one Black, were both documented using English-based creole phonological features, but only the Black speaker used creole morphosyntactic features \parencite[Rickford, 1985, as cited in][pp.~390-391]{fought_ethnicity_2013}.
      In California, both White and Latinx students were reported exploiting a phonological variable, but within the Latinx group, this variable also indexed their place in the social order of the school \parencite{eckert_where_2008}.
      These sort of cases of drawing from language varieties associated with other groups in different ways and to different degrees led \textcite{benor_ethnolinguistic_2010} to codify this in her ethnolinguistic repertoire framework.
      She described an ethnolinguistic repertoire as ``a fluid set of linguistic resources that members of an ethnic group may use variably as they index their ethnic identities'' (p.~160).
      While it might seem as though this framework is meant only for dealing with ethnicity, Benor made clear that the it could be used for non-ethnic identities, as well.

      What this discussion of crossing racial and ethnic boundaries often exemplifies is approaches to constructing racial and ethnic identities, but constructing racial and ethnic identities through language is also influenced by other social factors.
      National identity was seen as an important factor in the identity construction of Latinas in California \parencite{mendoza-denton_homegirls:_2008}, while socioeconomic class was seen to create problems for African-American identity construction in terms of having to navigate maintaining one's identitly while facing pressure to change for greater economic opportunities \parencite{rahman_middle-class_2008}.
      Even being bilingual can be a source of tension relevant to racial and ethnic identity construction.
      \textcite{rosa_looking_2019} argued that language and race ideologies delegitimize the use of both languages that bilinguals possess in that they are treated as imperfect speakers of both not because their speech is not structured similar to monolinguals of both languages but because perceptions of their speech are tainted by racial ideologies and concepts of authenticity (pp.~125-127).
      Racialized people thus face great societal pressure that constrains their ability to construct their identities through linguistic means as they see fit.
      % In New York, Asian and non-Asian speakers differed in their realizations of /ɛ/ and breathiness with Asian men producing more fronted variants and breathier speech (Newman & Wu 2011:166/168)
      % A Lumbee Indian being interviewed by a African-American Cherokee showed how ethnic identity can be linguistically negotiated in real time as the speakers' speech was most different when discussing race and most similar while discussing friends and family (Schilling-Estes 2004)

      \textcite{rosa_unsettling_2017} brought work on race in sociology, where race is initially imposed on a people through colonial processes, into sociolinguistics to improve analyses of racialized language.
      Their raciolinguistic perspective was indeed centered on the idea that the naturalization (\foreign{i.e.}, the act of making something seem natural) of races and languages with those races was a ``central component[] of the European colonial formation of modernity'' (p.~623).
      In other words, language was used as another way to mark racialized people and maintain dominance over them.
      As an example, AAL speakers have been shown to be routinely identified as Black and consequently more frequently denied housing opportunities when calling rental and sales offices \parencite{lanehart_swb_2015}.
      While the subordination of racialized people has not been ignored in the literature before \textcite{rosa_unsettling_2017}, it has been brought more to the forefront as have the sociological tools for analyzing it.
      % Linguicism or "'linguistically argued racism'" exists (Skutnabb-Kangas 1988; Phillipson 1992, as cited in Rosa 2019:139), which is used because biologically argued racism is no longer accepted in public discourse but linguistically argued racism is (Uricuoli 1996, 2001; Zentella 2007, as cited in Rosa 2019:139)
      % Rosa & Flores (2017) stuff
        % Hierarchically then, non-European languages were also placed below European languages (Makoni & Pennycook 2007; Veronelli 2015, as cited in Rosa & Flores 2017:623)
        % They called this linking of language and racial identity raciolinguistic enregisterment (Rosa & Flores 2017:631) after Agha's enregisterment (2003)
        % Racialized Others are unable to overcome this naturalization even when they learn the language of their oppressors which is still perceived as linguistically lacking (Rosa & Flores 2017:625, citing others)
          % This has important implications as language skills can be seen as a commodity (Rosa & Flores 2017:638, citing Heller & Duchêne 2012 as giving examples)
        % Bonfiglio (2002, 2010) argued that categories such as "Standard American English" and "native speaker" should be understood as representing racialized perceptions where anything associated with the dominant group is unmarked and anything associated with the dominated racialized group is inherently deficient (as cited in Rosa & Flores 2017:632)
      % Rosa & Flores (2017) proposed that perceptual work on race should refuse to analyze the production of racialized people and instead look at how listeners employ their race and language ideologies in interpreting racialized people (628-629)
        % This approach has not really been taken up for the obvious reason that knowing what racialized people are objectively producing is a necessary step in interpreting how a listeners ideologies are shaping what they are hearing
      % A natural response to the issues this framework raises is to propose affirming the language of racialized populations and providing them access to the tools needed to learn dominant ways of speaking, but this solution ignores the problems inherent in the racialized social system itself and puts the burden on racialized people to do more than others need to do (Rosa & Flores 2017:639)

      Race has, in sum, always held a prominent place in sociolinguistics despite having been dealt with differently over time.
      Early work did much to establish AAL and other language varieties associated with racialized groups as rule-bound and logical.
      Second and early third wave studies began looking more closely at local categories while giving more fine-grained analyses of broader social categories.
      It was also at that time that the validity of social categories was questioned.
      It has not been until relatively recently, however, that sociological work on race has found its way into sociolinguistics, although there is still much to add to the literature in terms of incorporating the theories of racial formation and racialized social systems into sociolinguistic analyses.

