  \section{The history of Creole people}
    \label{sec:creole_history}
    When focusing in on race and ethnicity in Louisiana, two social categories that are often evoked are Creole and Cajun, hence these are the categories being examined here to help shed light on racialization in the state.
    The former category and the related group have a rather complex and winding history.
    At the outset of the colonization of Louisiana, a Creole was simply someone born in the colony regardless.\footnote{
      It is notable that American Indians who resided in the territory have not figured into discussions in the literature about who was and who was not considered a Creole in the early colonial history of Louisiana, although they were quite obviously being born in the territory.
    }
    This was not a particularly distinguishing status until the Louisiana Purchase, at which time the arrival of Americans made being a Creole something more notable than it had been previously.
    After the Civil War and through much of the Jim Crow years, there were efforts to redefine the term as applying to only Whites of French or Spanish descent, but this effort was not entirely successful as perhaps the most common understanding of Creole for Louisianians today is as something of a synonym for Black.
    These developments will be discussed in more detail in this section to elucidate what the path to racialization of a people looks like or otherwise how it is avoided.
    
    % In mid- to late-19th century New Orleans, for example, the term could be used in such a generalized way that it was applied to food as a synonym for local \parencite[p.~21]{johnson_louisiana_1976}.
    % For people, however, the term has been applied to variously to groups such as those of French and/or Spanish descent born in Louisiana and those of mixed African and European descent \parencite{dominguez_social_1977}.
    % It is also common to encounter Louisianians today who equate \lexi{Creole} with \lexi{Black}.
    % My own participants were all asked to define what a Creole is, and the topic consistently evoked strong reactions that suggested that the answer for them is long and complicated, especially when the question was put to my Cajun participants.
    % When discussing Creoles in terms of non-Whites, \textcite{susberry_racial_2004} suggested that interest has been maintained due to concern over Louisiana exports being marketed as ``Cajun'' and thereby erasing Creole contributions, the lack of laws or even census options that lead to pigeonholing Creoles as Black, an indirectly related focus on French language education in Louisiana, and the popularity of geneological research in the state (p.~14), although on this last point, I would argue that geneological research is popular because Creole and especially Cajun identities are tightly linked to one's ancestry in the minds of residents, as will become apparent in the ensuing discussions.

    Much of the research on the various stages in the development of the definition of Creoles has focused on New Orleans rather than the state as a whole.
    This caveat to the ensuing discussion could be explained due to the city simply being a more attractive object of study for historians or perhaps to a lack of primary data for the areas outside of New Orleans.
    However, especially for the 18th century, this is a sensible focus as New Orleans was the colonial population center of the territory.
    Censuses of rural plantations and other settlements in South Louisiana in the 1700s were not numerous but did exist (\citeauthor{mills_family_1981}, \citeyear[p.~27]{mills_family_1981}; \citeauthor{zitomersky_urbanization_1974}, \citeyear[pp.~276-277]{zitomersky_urbanization_1974}).
    These numbers indicate that, for example, there were 4,983 colonists and enslaved people living in the territory of modern day Louisiana, not including American Indians nor women, of which 1,183 or about 24\% were outside of New Orleans, mostly in Pointe Coupee \parencite[p.~177]{hall_africans_1992}.
    In contrast, there were 1,005,281 people estimated to reside in the entire New Orleans metropolitan area in 2020 \parencite{us_census_bureau_metropolitan_2020} compared to the 4,657,757 living in the entire state \parencite{us_census_bureau_us_2020}, meaning that roughly 78\% of the population was living outside of New Orleans.
    The region of focus for this study is around the Lafayette area, a good distance from New Orleans, so research specifically on that area rather than on New Orleans would be ideal, but given the disparity in population, it is still reasonable to assume that early views on Creoles were not significantly different in the rural areas of Louisiana from in New Orleans.
    As the rural population increased later in the 19th century and beyond, more research also becomes available from rural perspectives.
    % Up to the Louisiana Purchase
      % Natchitoches was the first permanent colonial settlement in 1714 (E. S. Mills 1981:3)
        % Census figures suggest that the population grew from 62 in 1722 to 1,778 in 1802 (E. S. Mills 1981:27)
          % During these years, the percentage of non-White residents wavered around 50%, although Creole didn't mean non-White at that time
        % These numbers look quite different from what G. M. Hall (1992) reported for 1746, though

    The term \lexi{Creole} was originally just a synonym for local or native to the colonies of the American continents, a usage that dates back at least as far back as 1731 according to baptismal records from New Orleans \parencite[pp.~95-97]{dominguez_white_1986}.
    This means not only were French and Spanish colonists considered to be Creoles but so were many enslaved Africans.
    Likewise, free people of color, often referred to by with the French term \foreign{gens de couleur libres}, were uncontroversially described as Creoles when they were born in Louisiana.

    Free people of color were not unique to Louisiana, but they were particularly common there.
    They were also regularly implicated in redefinitions of the term \lexi{Creole}, especially during Reconstruction.
    A court case involving one François Tioucou suggests that Free People of Color were present in New Orleans since at least the early 18th century.
    Tioucou was not, however, a Creole as he was born in Africa \parencite[pp.~32-33]{everett_free_1966}, meaning that free person of color did not necessarily imply Creole at that time.
    A common path to freedom for those born in Louisiana was through a system known as plaçage in which free men entered into relationships with enslaved women or free women of color that in many ways resembled marriages.
    According to the French Black Code or \foreign{Code noire} that was in effect at that time, free men were not permitted to marry nor ``vivre en concubinage''\footnote{
      Cohabit.
    } \parencite[pp.~3-4]{louis_xv_code_1727}.
    Despite this, the lopsided male and female populations in the region provided White men with an incentive to have these liaisons anyway.
    According to census records, in 1721 there were 293 men but only 140 women in rural Louisiana \parencite[Beer, 1911, as cited in][pp.~15-16]{klingler_if_2003}.
    Relatedly, funeral records from the late 18th century suggest a median age of 30.6 for White men and 30.3 for free women of color but only 18.1 for White women and 8.1 for free men of color \parencite[p.~220]{hanger_coping_1997}.
    The simplest path towards creating a family was thus with enslaved women or free women of color.
    For the women, particularly enslaved women, these relationships offered them benefits up to the possibility of freedom for them and their offspring, hence becoming free people of color.
    The practice thus continued through the 18th century as well as the 19th century.
    Indeed, firsthand reports indicated that balls for arranging these relationships were being held in first half of the 19th century (\citeauthor{featherstonhaugh_excursion_1968}, \citeyear[pp.~141-142]{featherstonhaugh_excursion_1968}; \citeauthor{latrobe_southern_1986}, \citeyear[p.~77]{latrobe_southern_1986}).
    % Only 6 "mulattoes" were in the 1732 census for New Orleans (Everett 1966:32-33)
    % The Black Code gave children the status of their mothers (Louis XV 1727:4)
    % Canon (1995) argued that the choices of oppressed groups are necessarily constrained by their circumstances (as cited in J. Martin 2000:64)

    % Anderson (1983/2006) also understood Creole and Criollo in the New World to mean a "person of (at least theoretically) pure European descent but born in the Americas" (47)
      % Anderson (1983/2006) argued that Creoles were excluded from being Europeans despite being generally indistinguishable physically and cultural, so they felt compelled to hold themselves above locals and mixed people in the New World, which for him "foreshadows modern racism" (59-60)

    Plaçage arrangements could take on various forms.
    In some cases, these were lifelong commitments, whereas in others they might have lasted a few years, often ending when the man entered into a legal marriage with a White woman.
    \textcite{martineau_society_1966-1}, getting her information from ``ladies who cannot be mistaken,'' suggested that for the enslaved women and free women of color afterward, the dissolution of the relationship meant the end of any possibility for another relationship for the rest of their lives.
    Some committed suicide while ``more die[d] broken-hearted'' (pp.~326-327).
    The latter result was perhaps poetic musing on the part of Martineau despite the methodological rigor of this early sociological work, as all accounts suggest that plaçage was a practical matter for these women rather than a matter of love.
    For this reason, \textcite{kein_placage_2000} characterized women's choice to enter into plaçage as a matter of doing whatever they could to survive given their limited life options (p.~65).
    Enslaved women and free women of color wanted to attain a higher social status and, in the case of the former, rights by having children to White men and even gaining inheritances in the process.
    % Martineau (1837/1966) reported discussions of Quadroon women (free or enslaved) that she had with "ladies who cannot be mistaken" (326-327)
      % They are "highly educated, externally, and are, probably, as beautiful and accomplished a set of women as can be found" (326)

    Children who came out of the plaçage system were of course considered Creoles just as any Whites, enslaved people, or free people of color who were born in the colony.
    This use of the term \lexi{Creole} as locally born was still commonly seen in newspapers in the 1820s and 1830s where it was even applied to Anglo-Americans and Acadians\footnote{
      Acadians, whose name evolved into Cajun, will be discussed in their own right in section \ref{sec:cajun_history}.
    } exiled from modern-day Canada who had been born in Louisiana.
    In the case of the latter, it was particularly well established that the press viewed Alexandre Mouton, an Acadian and eleventh governor of Louisiana from 1843 to 1846, as a Creole \parencite[pp.~23-24]{tregle_early_1952}.
    Despite this ongoing use of \lexi{Creole} to mean local or native, it has also been argued that the Louisiana Purchase in 1803 entailed the beginning of a shift towards the fact of being a Creole being a distinguishing feature of one's identity \parencite[pp.~134-135]{hirsch_creoles_1992}.

    The impact that the arrival of Americans had on the identity and status of Creoles was perhaps initially felt most directly by free people of color.
    At the outset of the 19th century, free people of color were certainly not the social and legal equals of Whites, but they did enjoy significantly more rights than enslaved people.
    Free people of color were able to obtain an education, use the courts, work, and own property \parencite[p.~34]{tregle_early_1952}.
    Notorial acts in New Orleans show that they were at least trading in real estate, boats, lumber, and jewelry \parencite[p.~242]{hanger_avenues_1990}.
    Such trading resulted in free people of color in New orleans owning an estimated \$2 million in assets in 1836 which increased to between \$13 million and \$15 million by 1860, all of which included owning enslaved people \parencite[p.~15]{stone_negro_1900}.
    Indeed, in opposition to proposed legislation that would strip the right of free people of color to own property, a newspaper editorial from 1852 argued that free people of color were more disdainful of enslaved people than even Whites were, meaning that Whites had no need to fear free people of color upsetting the social order.
    The proposal was ultimately not passed nor did another proposal in 1846 to remove the right of free people of color to bear witness in court.
    In this case, one can easily see the fragile intermediate social status of free people of color in the argument that the chair of the judiciary committee made against the measure in the legislature.
    The chair argued that rescinding this right was inconvenient for the courts, adding that laws should aim to ``elevate, not degrade'' the ``better class'' of free people of color \parencite[pp.~172-175]{sterkx_free_1972}.
    In this one argument, it was signaled that free people of color were intimately linked to a lower class of people even while suggesting that they should be raised up and supported.

    Though the effort to remove the rights of free people of color to own property and to bear witness in court failed, this move highlights the continual deterioration of the rights of free people of color throughout the 1800s as Whites became more and more unsettled by their status, wanting instead to collapse them in with enslaved people.
    These moves started shortly after the Louisiana Purchase when a new Black Code was enacted in 1807 along with additional related acts.
    Included in this new legislation were provisions that required enslaved people to be at least 30 years old and in good standing for at least the last four years in order to be eligibly for manumission, the intended effect being to make it more difficult to be freed \parencite[p.~83]{territory_of_orleans_acts_1807-1}.
    The Civil Code of 1808 also reaffirmed that marriage between a free and enslaved person would be illegal as well as between a White person and a free person of color \parencite[p.~25]{dominguez_white_1986}.
    
    While these laws greatly limited avenues towards greater rights for enslaved people and in part for free people of color, as well, actions were also taken to official limit the economic prospects of free people of color.
    \court{Boisdoré and Goulé v.~Bank} was a case in 1833 involving Citizens Bank of New Orleans who asserted that they had a right to refuse to sell stocks to free people of color.
    Their argument ultimately convinced the court, paving the way for a reduction in the ability to own assets or even participate in business ventures \parencite[p.~52]{kein_marcus_2000}.
    Perhaps even more deleterious, however, was the result of \court{Jung v.~Doriscourts et al.}~the year before, which established that the French inheritance laws that had been in effect up to that point, which allowed children born via plaçage arrangements to inherit the father's wealth, were no longer valid \parencite[p.~231]{johnston_race_1970}.
    All these of these actions had the effect of undermining the purpose of the plaçage system for enslaved people and free people of color while also making it more difficult to be freed in the first place and more difficult to get ahead once freed, bringing free people of color closer in line with the lot of enslaved people.

    Attempts to collapse free people of color and enslaved people into one category intensified further after the Civil War.
    Louisiana was in a state of financial ruin \parencite[pp.~428-429]{winters_civil_1963}, and that combined with the loss of the war and finding even more Blacks walking freely left Whites feeling that that place in the social order was insecure.
    Indeed, animosity towards Blacks commonly found expression in newspapers.
    In some cases, these articles even found Whites explicitly linking their feelings of animosity to the results of the war \parencite[pp.~173-175]{blassingame_black_1973}.
    Public calls were soon being made for all Louisianians, all Creoles, to declare themselves either Black or White and nothing in between.
    For their part, former free people of color, not immune to the change in fortunes in the state, were split on whether to align themselves with formerly enslaved people or with Whites \parencite[p.~135-137]{dominguez_white_1986}.
    For Whites, the choice of how to racially identify former free people of color was not a difficult one.

    While the term \lexi{Creole} was applied to Whites, free people of color, and enslaved people through much of the 19th century, it was after the war that the ``Creole myth'' came about, asserting that only those of pure White blood were Creoles \parencite{hirsch_creoles_1992}.
    In the most innocuous of perpetuations of this myth, one finds clarifying appositions in letters such as one from 1878 that equate Creoles with those ``of French descent'' in contrast to Americans who were those ``of English descent'' \parencite[p.~245]{mccants_they_1970}.
    Something of the old definition still resides in this contrast as Americans, especially when referred to in F\&C (\foreign{i.e.}, \foreign{les Américains}), is said even today to refer to those who are not from South Louisiana, but the emphasis on French descent suggests a White European identity for Creoles as the other end of that contrast.
    In other perpetuations of the myth, there was the addition of the romanticized idea of Creoles having been a sort of aristocratic class.
    \textcite{fortier_french_1884} described Creoles as specifically Whites born in the Americans with either French or Spanish heritage, arguing that they ``occupied a high standing'' before the war (p.~98).
    His evidence was a list of successful politicians going back to the second governor of the US state, a list that was in fact in direct contradiction to the original use of the term \lexi{Creole} as it included people like the fifth governor of Louisiana, Pierre Derbigny, who was born in France.
    Finally, some perpetuations of the myth were rather dehumanizing.
    For example, \textcite{tinker_toucoutou_1928}, writing well after Reconstruction, did not disregard that non-Whites were described as Creoles but rather claimed that this was always with a lowercase \orth{c} indicating an adjective as could be applied to any type of Louisiana product: carrots, eggs, or in this case people (pp.~7-8).
    Of course, Tinker did not provide any evidence for this claim, and it flies in the face of much of the evidence already discussed here.

    The Creole myth was likely more successful at redefining who Creoles were during the colonial and antebellum periods than in redefining Creoles contemporaneously.
    There were and still are people who openly identify as Creoles of color, although they have been effectively aggregated into the Black side of a Black-White racial dichotomy that has been pursued since Reconstruction.
    By the turn of the century, those who were not White or could not pass for White were subject to Jim Crow laws such as the poll tax that was implemented by the Louisiana constitution of 1898 \parencite[pp.~80-81]{louisiana_constitution_1898}.
    This created the impetus for some Creoles of color to attempt to pass as White.
    The practice of passing has been documented in New Orleans where families would pass for the sake of the success of their businesses in the 1940s.
    Some in the 1970s and 1980s continued the practice, as well, sometimes passing in all social contexts, sometimes in limited contexts, sometimes asserting their Whiteness so forcefully that they deny their heritage and sometimes not \parencite[pp.~200-203]{dominguez_white_1986}.
    Situations such as this are why \textcite{kein_placage_2000} argued that the tenuous existence of Creoles of color has created a schism between them and non-Creole Blacks that endured up until her time at least (pp.~69-70).
    Indeed, the drastic changes in the social and political landscape since the first Creoles came about have resulted in the category and by extension the people difficult to pin down.

    More recently, researchers have attempted to pin down the definition of Creole by asserting that they are multiracial people.
    \textcite{susberry_racial_2004} defined them as ``[m]ultiracial people whose ancestral history is connected to Louisiana'' (p.~8), while \textcite{giancarlo_dont_2019} stated that they are mixed race people with French cultural origins (p.~42), although it is not entirely clear what it means to have French cultural origins.
    These definitions harken back in particular to free people of color who, when born of the plaçage system, were given racial designations based on the presumed mixture of Black and White races in their ancestry \parencite[p.~35]{tregle_early_1952}.
    Centering the definition on multiracial people does not entirely contradict the original sense of local or native but does prevent those who do not claim a mixed ancestry from identifying as Creole.
    That said, some of my own participants used the idea of racial mixture as an aspect of being Creole.
    % Definitions (researchers)
      % In general, Susberry (2004) found that ethnic identity achievement, self-esteem, self-perceived skin color, and "Creole dialect" fluency had statistically significant impacts on racial identifications, but negative treatment by Whites, negative treatment by Blacks, and the perceived social status of Blacks were not statistically significant (47)
        % Creoles of Color who identified as Black believed they appeared Black to others whereas those who identified as Creole believed they appeared ambiguous to others, suggesting a link between beliefs about their own appearances to others and how they choose to self-identify (Susberry 2004:45/48)
          % An implication is that one needs to be able to at least believe that society doesn't see them as Black in order for them to self-identify as Creole, though it's not clear if this held true for my own participants.

    Louisianians themselves have indeed been documented as highlighting a mixed racial ancestry as a criteria for being Creole, although not always.
    The Creoles of color with whom \parencite{susberry_racial_2004} worked described Creoles as mixed race while also suggesting that they have a French or Spanish history that is linked specifically to South Louisiana (p.~56), the latter feature being one invented for the White Creole myth that has evidently spilled into modern non-White definitions of \lexi{Creole}.
    This linkage to French or Spanish ancestry resulted in some participants being unaware of their eligibility to claim a Creole identity until later in life (p.~59).
    Other Creoles of color in \citeauthor{susberry_racial_2004}'s (\citeyear{susberry_racial_2004}) study took the term to be more of a cultural concept.
    The implicated cultural features implicated are by and large shared with Cajuns, though neither Cajuns not Creoles themselves accepted participation in such culture as a sufficient criteria for being Cajun if one was also considered Black (\citeauthor{esman_henderson_1985}, \citeyear[p.~7]{esman_henderson_1985}; \citeauthor{spitzer_cajuns_1977}, \citeyear{spitzer_cajuns_1977}).
    In other words, Cajun has become a specifically White identity and Creole a non-White identity.
    It has thus been argued by some that the most common definition for Creoles in recent times is someone with African ancestry and roots in Louisiana \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][pp.~39-40]{eble_creole_2008}, which is a common finding when study participants in Louisiana are interrogated about their identities.
    \textcite{klingler_language_2003}, for instance, found that all 19 of his participants in St Landry Parish who identified as Creole also identified as Black (p.~82).

    Those who in the past might have identified as White Creoles, in contrast, have become much more likely to identify as Cajun.
    Where \lexi{Cajun} had been a derogatory term even up to the mid 1970s, it was transformed into a positive, catch-all term for White South Louisianians by the early 1980s largely through the efforts of the Council for the Development of French in Louisiana (CODOFIL) \parencite[pp.~164-167]{trepanier_cajunization_1991}.
    However, as \textcite{eble_creole_2008} observed, there are Louisianians ``from a wide range of ethnic backgrounds'' who have been attempting to revive the old meaning of Creole as simply meaning native (p.~49).
    Indeed, cultural activists in the state such as Gene Buller and John LaFleur II have rejected the Cajun branding of all things South Louisiana and instead promoted Creole branding at least in part because it is inclusive for both Whites and Blacks.
    Their approach is however not a simple revival of Creole as a synonym for native, as Eble claimed, but rather as inclusive of anyone who has European ancestors regardless of whether they also have African and/or American Indian ancestors \parencite{partsch_creole_2015}.
    The reclamation is rather a partial deracialization of the term, partial as European hegemony is a part of what constitutes White hegemony in the US.

