  \section{The history of Cajuns}
    \label{sec:cajun_history}
    The history of Cajuns in Louisiana is intimately tied to that of the Acadians who resided in what is now Nova Scotia.
    This link exists both in fact and imagination.
    Indeed, the expulsion of the Acadians from Canada in the 18th century, called the \foreign{Grand dérangement}, is central to the origin story of the Cajuns of Louisiana today so much so that Henry Wadsworth Longfellow's \titlebook{Evangeline} romanticized the expulsion of the Acadians from Canada and is well known in South Louisiana for this reason despite the main character only spending a very short amount of time in the state \parencite{ross_evangeline_1991}.
    The term \lexi{Cajun} itself is derived from French \lexi{Acadien}, both the form with and without the initial vowel being used at various times in history for various reasons \parencite{henry_acadien_1998}, a fact that any French-speaking Cajun today will likely be able to reiterate.
    % Alveolar stops before vowels and especially /j/ are affricated in Terrebonne-Lafourche (Papen & Rottet 1997:77)

    The Acadians themselves arrived in North America from mainly the western parts of France, namely Poitou, Aunis, Saintonge, and Angoumois \parencite{massignon_parlers_1962}, though it is unlikely that their ancestry remained purely French.
    Their first settlement, Port Royal, was founded in 1605 \parencite[p.~17]{massignon_parlers_1962}, establishing them in a region already occupied by American Indians such as the Mi'kmaq.
    While there is still much to uncover about the relationship between the French Acadians and the Mi'kmaq,, what textual evidence that has been analyzed as well as the demographic realities of colonial life that would have left few options for the creation of families make it ``highly likely'' that Mi'kmaqs were assimilated as Acadians and vice versa \parencite[pp.~22-25]{griffiths_contexts_1992}.
    Regardless, the people of this region who came to be called Acadians were suspected of being loyal to France after the territory came into British power with the Treaty of Utrecht in 1713.
    The British had insisted that they swear an oath of allegiance to Britian instead.
    The refusal of the Acadians to do did little to assuage suspicions, and by 1755 they were forcibly exiled from their home \parencite{faragher_great_2005}.

    Those Acadians who ended up settling in Louisiana did not arrive directly from Acadia.
    For instance, 1,508 had returned to France who did not necessarily want them back.
    Louisiana by this time was controlled by Spain, and Spain's ambassador in Paris, Count de Aranda, was charged with removing the Acadians from France and settling them in Louisiana \parencite[p.~109]{winzerling_acadian_1955}.
    Being once again forced to relocate may have helped create tensions between the Spanish and the Acadians as as some of those who would end up in the areas outside of New Orleans joined an insurrection in the city against the Spanish colonists in favor of the French in 1768 \parencite[p.~39]{texada_administration_1968}.
    The Acadians relocated from France, along with roughly 1,200 to 1,500 others eventually landed in Louisiana, initially settling in the Attakapas, the Acadian Coast along the Mississippi, and Natchez \parencite[pp.~74-78/91-100]{brasseaux_foundings_1987}.
    The distance between Natchez and the Acadian Coast is roughly 250 miles, covering a large amount of rural South Louisiana.
    Being able to connect one lineage to some degree to these early families was an important criteria for claiming Cajun identity up to at least the end of the 20th century \parencite[p.~184]{ryon_conflit_2000}, although those lines of descent are not often straightforward, as will be discussed shortly.
      
    Whereas the Creole myth discussed in section \ref{sec:creole_history} characterized Creoles of the past as aristocratic, the picture of Cajuns has been consistently of an impoverished people.
    In his journey through Louisiana in the first half of the 19th century, \parencite{olmsted_journey_1904} was told that the ``Acadians'' whose ``hamlet of cottages'' they passed were ``poor white, French Creoles'' (p.~342).
    This use of \lexi{Creole} suggests that the term was applied to more Acadians/Cajuns than Alexandre Mouton as previously mentioned \parencite{tregle_early_1952, tregle_that_1982} but to Acadians/Cajuns in general.
    Importantly, however, Cajuns were not rich Creoles at all.
    Accounts made by traveling Northerners after the war described ``Acadians'' as white trash, poor, uneducated, lazy, primitive, unambitious to where, by the late 19th century, Americans used the term \lexi{Cajun} to describe any poor person of French descent \parencite[pp.~101-104]{brasseaux_acadian_1992}.
    Indeed, \lexi{Cajun} had become a derogatory word, as \textcite{ralph_along_1893}, during his travels in Louisiana, was warned not to call (White) Acadians in Bayou Têche ``Cajun'' without the \orth{A} as this would be considered an insult (p.~883).
    
    While it is clear that a stigma was being attached to Cajuns already by the 19th century based on their low socioeconomic status, especially when using the localized version of their name, Cajuns were not an entirely homogenous group.
    Even in terms of their financial situations, while many were poor, some were sufficiently well off that they owned enslaved people.
    The first such documentation of this was as early as the 1770s \parencite[p.~191]{brasseaux_foundings_1987}.
    Census records from the 1850s in Lafayette Parish suggest that this practice continued and became relatively normal for Cajuns, although most who owned enslaved people own very few of them \parencite{baker_patterns_1974}.
    Additionally, while it has been argued that Cajuns in the 19th century were not very successful at forming sociopolitical alliances with other groups \parencite[p.~27]{johnson_louisiana_1976}, exogamous marriages did occur.
    Cajun women outnumbered Cajun men up to at least the Civil War and so often married non-Cajun men.
    In Terrebonne-Lafourche, as many as 40\% of the Cajun women who married chose men from outside their group such as Germans.
    As a result, their family names changed to non-Acadian names or even non-French names, yet their children were still raised as Cajuns \parencite[pp.~38-39/106]{brasseaux_acadian_1992}, hence how some early Cajun families ended up with unexpected names when conceptualizing Cajun as those with Acadian ancestry.

    By the early 20th century, the image of Cajuns as poor was still the primary one.
    For example, \textcite{smith_influence_1939} argued that Cajuns lacked mobility largely due to their status as poor farmers (p.~198).
    Indeed, immobility and isolation had also become central to characterizations of Cajuns by that time to such an extent that it was argued that this had led them to be ``probably the largest unassimilated nationality group in America'' \parencite[p.~82]{gilmore_social_1933}.
    It is doubtful that Gilmore's use of ``nationality'' for Cajuns was meant to imply that they were a politically organized ethnic group in his view as sociologists use the term today but rather to imply that Cajuns were culturally foreigners in relation to other Americans.
    As far as \textcite{smith_influence_1939}, that was a sort of French nationality as they highlighted both being francophone and being ``of French descent,'' be it Acadian or otherwise, in their definition of Cajuns (p.~198).

    While Acadian ancestry never quite disappeared as a criteria for claiming Cajun membership, cultural factors came to be highlighted more by the 1970s.
    For \textcite{del_sesto_culture_1975}, for instance, Cajuns were Louisianians who were Catholic, rural, privileged kinship relationships, and spoke or at least knew speakers of French.
    They explicitly suggested that Cajuns were not only those whose ancestors were expelled from Acadia but also others who had been incorporated into the group over time (p.~3).
    \textcite{brown_pronominal_1988} went even further, claiming that ``someone who calls himself a Cajun today is no longer necessarily of Acadian ancestry,'' basing this on all of her participants claiming Cajun identity even though those from Avoyelles being of European ancestry and those from Pierre Part being of Acadian ancestry (pp.~18-20/22).
    It is unclear how she established the ancestry of her participants, although Avoyelles is just north of the areas where \textcite{brasseaux_foundings_1987} had shown that the Acadians initially settled.
    This does not mean that Acadians never spread north over time, however, which exemplifies the murkiness of using ancestry to establish Cajun membership and perhaps the reason why geneaology is such a prevalent topic for Louisianians today.

    In any case, Cajun membership has become easier to claim since the late 20th century.
    For one, the stigma that was once attached to Cajuns has transformed into pride since the 1970s through what has been dubbed the Cajun Renaissance.
    This movement was initially referred to as a ``renaissance du français'' \parencite[p.~40]{smith-thibodeaux_francophones_1977} or a ``renaissance française''\footnote{
      Renaissance of French or French Renaissance, respectively.
    } \parencite[p.~205]{waddell_louisiane_1979}.
    Much of the initial revalorization efforts were focused on the French language in Louisiana \parencite{smith-thibodeaux_francophones_1977}, a variety that was branded Cajun to the exclusion of Creoles, Indians, and others just as their role has been excluded from many other aspects of Louisiana culture \parencite{giancarlo_dont_2019}.
    The Renaissance itself has come to be labeled Cajun (\foreign{e.g.}, \citeauthor{dubois_when_1999}, \citeyear[p.~305]{dubois_when_1999}; \citeauthor{glain_cajun_2021}, \citeyear{glain_cajun_2021}), perhaps as a result of the diminished role of F\&C in the state as will be discussed in section \ref{sec:fc_status}.
    Indeed, \textcite{ryon_conflit_2000} found that, among college students at the University of Louisiana, Lafayette, French fluency was a sufficient criteria for Cajun membership, especially among men, but not a necessary criteria as 63\% of men and 42\% of women who identified as Cajun did not speak French with their families (pp.~180-182).
    Similarly, \citeauthor{tornquist_attitudes_2000}'s (\citeyear{tornquist_attitudes_2000}) survey of parents of French immersion students showed that 58\% of the parents who identified as Cajun spoke French (p.~188), meaning 42\% of the Cajun parents who valued the language enough to send their children to French immersion schools were unable to speak the language themselves.
    While efforts to re-establish pride in French in Louisiana started with the language, as the language continued to decline in importance, this newfound pride was instead projected on to Cajun identity in general.
    The movement has been successful enough that, by the 1990s, \textcite{rottet_language_1995} found the Cajuns of Terrebonne-Lafourche with whom he worked to no longer be stigmatized (p.~110).

    Today, cultural factors have continued to be used for defining Cajuns, but Cajun is also discussed as something along the line of a panethnicity \parencite{omi_racial_1997}.
    \textcite{dajko_sociolinguistics_2012} suggested that one could be Cajun through associations with foodways, music, the French language, ``and until recently, the Catholic faith,'' all of which she claimed could also be used as valid criteria for Creole membership (p.~280).
    Likewise, \citeauthor{ryon_conflit_2000}'s (\citeyear{ryon_conflit_2000}) college students also reported foodways and religion as important factors for claiming Cajun identity (p.~184).
    The similarity in what cultural features can be used for establishing Cajun and Creole membership is notable, however, as it has provided room for major racial categories from the US to be applied to these local categories.
    As already discussed in section \ref{sec:creole_history}, for many, Cajun has come to be more or less a synonym for White and Creole for not White.
    On the Cajun side, while being inclusive of essentially all White South Louisianians has perhaps provided the group with greater robustness and sociopolitical power, as is sometimes the motivation for other groups that come together to form a panethnicity, as \textcite{giancarlo_dont_2019} put it, it also ``minimizes a diversity of white ethnicities'' (p.~33) essentially through a form of erasure \parencite{irvine_language_2000}.
    Indeed, as one of \citeauthor{trepanier_cajunization_1991}'s (\citeyear{trepanier_cajunization_1991}) respondents from Breaux Bridge resentfully stated in 1981, ``On s'appelait des Créoles avant cette affaire de Cadjin''\footnote{
      We called ourselves Creoles before this Cajun business.
    } (p.~167).
    While all those born in South Louisiana were at one time Creoles including Cajuns, a realignment has occurred where these two categories are mutually exclusive and more in accord with the the broader US binary of White ersus non-White.
        
