  \section{The status of F\&C in Louisiana}
    \label{sec:fc_status}
    French fluency is not simply a factor that helps one claim Creole or Cajun membership but rather the glottonym Creoles and Cajuns choose for what they speak is entangled with their self-identifications regardless of the structural qualities of their speech.
    In St Landry Parish, an area from which much of the data for the present study comes, it was found that those who identified as Cajuns called their language French whereas those who identified as Creoles called their language Creole even when some Creoles used linguistic features typically marked as French and some Cajuns used those typically marked as Creole \parencite{klingler_language_2003}.
    In light of this intimate connections with identity and language in Louisiana, the linguistic focus of here is on F\%C.
    It is thus important to situate the status of French and Creole in the state.

    The arrival of F\&C in Louisiana is started simply with the colonization of the region by the French.
    This early group of Europeans have been dubbed \foreign{l'ancienne population}\footnote{The old/former population.}, who were followed by the arrival of several other major francophone groups at different times: \foreign{les Français étrangers}\footnote{The foreign French.}, the Acadians, and those coming from Saint-Domingue\footnote{Present-day Haiti.} \parencite[p.~19]{johnson_louisiana_1976}.
    Indeed, while the bulk of early colonists came from Île-de-France and Brittany \parencite[pp.~15-17]{brasseaux_french_2005}, immigration of French speakers continued even after the Louisiana Purchase up to the Civil War \parencite[p.~99]{fortier_french_1884}. % No source for any of these facts. Verify in Brasseaux 1990 maybe.
    This includes the even the period of Spanish rule from 1762 to 1800.
    As already covered in section \ref{sec:cajun_history}, the Acadians arrived in Louisiana primarily during this time, for example, but also those who immigrated in response to the French Revolution\footnote{
      The bulk of this latter group came just after 1800 when Spain gave over control of Louisiana, but it started while Spain was still in power.
    } \parencite{lachance_new_1989}.
    For those coming directly from France during this time the bulk came from Guyenne and Provence in the south of France, groups that made up an insignificant portion of early French colonists \parencite[p.~22]{brasseaux_french_2005}.
    % Louisiana was claimed in 1682 by René-Robert Cavelier de La Salle of French Canada (Neumann 1985:8)
      % Louisiana wasn't really explored and colonized until 1698 by Pierre Le Moyne (Sieur d'Iberville) and Jean Baptiste Le Moyne (Sieur de Bienville) (Neumann 1985:8)

    It is often maintained at least implicitly that Acadian French is the primary origin of the variety of French spoken in rural Louisiana.
    This idea has been challenged at least when applied to the entirety of South Louisiana \parencite{mathis-moser_how_2009}, mostly along demographic lines.
    For instance, in Avoyelles Parish and Pointe Coupée Parish at the fringes of where the Acadians initially settled, Cajuns made up only 1.6\% and 1.8\% of the population, respectively \parencite[p.~107]{brasseaux_acadian_1992}.
    On the other hand, Cajuns also outnumbered immigrants from France along Bayou Lafourche ten to one in 1870 \parencite[p.~168]{brasseaux_acadian_1992}, suggesting that in some regions of Louisiana, Acadians did in fact play an important role in the development of French in the state.
    Likewise, as \textcite{brown_pronominal_1988} argued, Acadian solidarity may have also provided them with outsized influence even where they were a minority of the population (pp.~21-22).
    Indeed, the population that arrived before the Acadians was not terribly cohesive in terms of cultural backgrounds and was often ephemeral.
    % Esman (1985) guessed that only 5% of the population of Louisiana in the 1980s had Acadian ancestry based on family names (7-8)
    % In fact, Arrighi (2014), a researcher focused on Acadian French, has even argued that data from Louisiana should be excluded from descriptions in the literature of "français acadien" (107)

    Another notable group of French-speaking immigrants that came to Louisiana slightly later were those from Saint-Domingue.
    Linguistically, there are implications for the development of Creole in Louisiana as some of those who arrived from Saint-Domingue may have brought there own Creole with them.
    Indicative of this are some of the Lomax recordings of songs in 1937 in New Orleans that contain syntactic structures reminiscent of Haitian Creole but not Louisiana Creole such as \foreign{Papa moin couru la rivière}\footnote{
      My father went to the river.
    } where the possessive determiner \lexi{moin} is postnominal rather than prenominal as it would be in Louisiana (\foreign{i.e.}, \foreign{Mon papa}) \parencite{klingler_creole_2024}.
    Over 10,000 people landed in New Orleans from Saint-Domingue in 1809 and 1810, making up the bulk of this group \parencite[p.~247]{brasseaux_1809_1992}.
    Work on surnames has suggested that there were additionally immigrants from this group who settled all across rural Louisiana in the 18th century as far west and north as Natchitoches \parencite[p.~23]{brasseaux_tortue_1992}, although it has not been clearly established to what degree if at all the French or Creole spoken by these immigrants contributed to the character of F\&C in rural Louisiana.
    % In 1788, the racial demographics of Saint-Domingue included approximately 28,000 Whites, 22,000 free people of color, and 405,000 enslaved people (Le Page & Tabouret-Keller 1985:50, citing the census)
    % Haitian independence was achieved in 1804 (Le Page & Tabouret 1985:50)

    By all accounts, French, Creole, and English were all widely spoken in Louisiana throughout the 19th century thanks to factors such as this continued francophone immigration.
    Indeed, the Louisiana legislature had appointed interpreters in order to deal with the multilingual nature of the state \parencite[pp.~97-98]{fortier_french_1884}.
    Starting with the Louisiana constitution of 1812, English was the official language of in which legislation was to be written \parencite{bush_first_1975}, but due to the fact that many in the legislature spoke only French, deliberations in French were tolerated \parencite[p.~33]{smith-thibodeaux_francophones_1977}.
    This continued in such a regular fashion that the 1845 constitution was written in both English and French and required the Secretary of the Senate and the Clerk of the House of Representatives to be bilingual \parencite[p.~12]{louisiana_constitution_1845}.
    Newspapers in French also suggest that the general public was literate in the language.
    These began being published in 1794 with \titlebook{Le Moniteur de la Louisiane}, and many others followed including perhaps the most famous, \titlebook{L'Abeille}, as well as \titlebook{L'Ami des ois}, \titlebook{Le Courrier de la Louisiane}, and \titlebook{Le Propagateur catholique}.
    \titlebook{L'Abeille} was not discontinued until 1925, and the last French-language newspaper was \titlebook{Le Courrier de la Nouvelle-Orléans} which was printed from 1902 until 1955 \parencite[p.~22]{johnson_louisiana_1976}.
    Other newspapers declined at the end of the 19th century, such as those in Pointe Coupée that ceased being published in 1872 \parencite[p.~108]{klingler_if_2003}
    % Even as late as the 1970s, the bilingual Acadiana Profile was launched (J. Johnson 1976:29), but this was clearly a niche item at that point
    % As I mentioned elsewhere, there were efforts to unify around language between the Louisiana Purchase and Civil War to resist the influence of "American" immigrants (J. Johnson 1976:20)

    French was ever-present enough in writing and day-to-day interactions that there are accounts that explicitly lay out language ideologies towards the various varieties used.
    In general, \textcite{fortier_french_1884} found the French of Louisiana to have a certain ``purity'' which he believed to be to due to the men of rich families having almost always been educated in France ``during the old regime.''
    As such, those francophones of little means were not seen in such a positive light.
    He particularly complained about Cajuns who degraded the language, in his view.
    He provided examples of their speech that were ``not very elegant'' such as the use of \lexi{je} as a first person plural subject pronoun, \lexi{paré} for \gloss{ready} rather than \lexi{prêt}, and \lexi{il mouille} for \gloss{it is raining} rather than \lexi{il pleut} (p.~99).
    Just as being a Cajun in the 19th century had become akin to being poor an uneducated, so was their language considered.
    % 1pl je is in fact a feature found even now in Acadian French (King 2000; Comeau & King 2007, both cited in King 2008:140)

    The decline of French in Louisiana, however, occurred most rapidly in the big city of New Orleans rather than in the rural areas populated by Cajuns.
    
